document_data.History:
Sometime ''circa'' the 1480s DR, Sangin was dispatched along with Dron and Utna by Count Strahd to [[Toril]] on the [[Prime Material plane]] to search for a specific magical item that could allow travel away from Barovia. While away from the [[Domains of Dread]] the Sangin and the [[lycanthrope]]s worked together to claim the item for themselves, as a means of escape from Strahd's ever-present and far-reaching control. 

[[File:Sangin Vamp.png|thumb|right|100px|Sangin the [[vampire]].]]
They tracked the item to the [[Temple of Kelemvor (Baldur's Gate)|temple of Kelemvor]] in [[Baldur's Gate]], and abducted the cleric [[Nerys Kathon]] to ''[[identify]]'' it from a group of other [[relic]]s. After successfully identifying an [[item enchantment|enchanted]] locket that once belonged to a woman named [[Tatyana]], Nerys withheld the information from her captors until she was rescued by the [[Heroes of Baldur's Gate]]. Unfortunately for everyone involved, Strahd tracked them down and used the mists of the [[Shadowfell]] to bring them all to his realm.
Once the group was returned to Strahd's domain, Sangin was promptly carried away by a cloud of [[bat]]s to [[Castle Ravenloft]]. Marked a traitor by the count, Sangin was feasted upon by three of Strahd's [[vampire]]s and turned into an [[undead]] monster himself.{{Cite comic/Shadows of the Vampire 2}} 

After his transformation, the vampiric Sangin was dispatched alongside his his sires to exert Strahd's control over the werewolf den, forcing the pack's leader [[Kiril]] to order the death of Dron.{{Cite comic/Shadows of the Vampire 3}} Bringing the werewolves along as brutish enforcers, Sangin and the vampires assailed [[Vargas|Baron Vargas]] for harboring the Heroes of Baldur's Gate, enemies of Barovia. In the ensuing battle, the undead Sangin was beheaded by Utna as revenge for Dron's death.{{Cite comic/Shadows of the Vampire 4}}
